we can see that the distribution of the variable "price per lb" is not normally distributed.A right-skewed graph indicates that there are more low values in the data set than high values.

Question-5, . Plot and understand the relationship between the variables 'numcol' and 'prodval' through scatterplot, and write your findings.¶

In [98]:
sns.set_style('whitegrid')
sns.scatterplot(x='numcol', y='prodvalue', data=df)

plt.title('Scatterplot of numcol vs prodval')
plt.xlabel('Number of Columns (numcol)')
plt.ylabel('Product Value (prodvalue)')

plt.show()
  • we can see that there is a positive linear relationship between the variables "numcol" and "prodval".
  • there is some variability in the data and the relationship is not perfectly linear.

QUESTION-7, Visualize and understand the relationship between the multiple pairs of variables throughout different years using pairplot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol', 'total prod', 'prodvalue','year')¶

In [110]:
PRPLT = ['numcol', 'yieldpercol', 'totalprod', 'prodvalue', 'year']
sns.pairplot(df[PRPLT], hue="year")
plt.show()
  • positive linear relationship between "numcol" and "total prod". As the number of colonies increases, the total production also tends to increase
  • positive linear relationship between "yield percol" and "total prod". As the yield per colony increases, the total production also tends to increase.
  • positive linear relationship between "total prod" and "prodvalue". As the total production increases, the production value also tends to increase.
  • we can see that the relationships between these variables remain relatively consistent across different years. This suggests that these relationships are relatively stable over time and may be useful for predicting future outcomes.

QUESTION-8, Display the correlation values using a plot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol','total prod', 'stocks', 'price per lb', 'prodvalue')¶

In [115]:
CORR = ['numcol', 'yieldpercol', 'totalprod', 'stocks', 'priceperlb', 'prodvalue']
correlation=df[CORR]
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of Selected Columns')
corr_matrix = correlation.corr()
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot= True);

by using heatmap, we can see the lots of correlation values¶

  • There is a moderate positive correlation (0.62) between "yield percol" and "total prod"
  • There is a strong positive correlation (0.85) between "total prod" and "prodvalue".
  • There is a moderate negative correlation (-0.50) between "stocks" and "price per lb".
  • There is a strong positive correlation (0.91) between "numcol" and "total prod".
  • the heatmap provides a comprehensive visualization of the correlation values between multiple columns.
